4. Experimental Methodology
In this paper Ô¨Åve diÔ¨Äerent heuristics for choosing values of m are compared. They are: Ô¨Åxed [4], random selection [5], angle-based selection [6], and two heuristics using reinforcement learning. This section Ô¨Årst presents these
Ô¨Åve heuristics in more detail and then describes the testing methodology.
4.1. Heuristics for choosing m
The Ô¨Åve heuristics are:
GMRES(m): the original restarted GMRES algorithm with a Ô¨Åxed restart value of m.
randGMRES(m1 , m2 , . . . mk ): randomly chooses from a set of k restart values {m1 , m2 , . . . mk }. With this notation
the version tested in [5] would be written as randGMRES(10, 11, 12, . . . , 30) and randGMRES(m) would be
equivalent to GMRES(m).
angleGMRES(m1 , m2 , . . . mk ): chooses restart values from the ordered list {m1 , m2 , . . . mk } based on the convergence
rate as measured by the ratio between consecutive residual norms. If the norm of the residual is decreasing
at least as fast as some user-speciÔ¨Åed rate then the restart value is not changed. Otherwise, the restart value
changes to the next value in the list, cycling to the beginning of the list if necessary. With this notation, the
version in [6] would be written as angleGMRES(30, 27, . . . , 6, 3).
GMRES RL(m1 , m2 , . . . mk ): uses reinforcement learning with a reward function that returns the negative of the
restart value chosen.
angleGMRES RL(m1 , m2 , . . . mk ): identical to GMRES RL except the reward function adds in the selected restart
value scaled by the angle between consecutive residual vectors.
The above description of the two reinforcement learning based heuristics speciÔ¨Åes only the reward function. However, using reinforcement learning requires specifying states, actions, a reward function, a policy, and a function for
updating the value function. These are speciÔ¨Åed as follows:
‚Ä¢ states: 11 states based on the magnitude of the norm of the residual. One state represents the initial conÔ¨Åguration
in the Ô¨Årst iteration when the residual has yet to be computed. One represents convergence, in which the norm
is less than or equal to 10‚àí8 . The remaining states each represent a power of 10 between 1 and 10‚àí8 .
‚Ä¢ actions: choosing a value of m from varying subsets of {10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60}. (The possible restart values was
restricted to a small set in order to allow more concrete comparisons between the diÔ¨Äerent heuristics.)
‚Ä¢ policy: an -greedy policy, which means the action taken is the best one according to the current estimated
value function (1 ‚àí ) ¬∑ 100 percent of the time, and the action taken is chosen at random the remaining ( ¬∑ 100)
percent of the time. The heuristics tested here used = 0.2.
‚Ä¢ update function: one-step Q-learning, which means the estimated value of Q is modiÔ¨Åed by the immediate
reward and an estimate of the future reward. This learning policy takes two parameters which control the
relative weights of the immediate and future rewards. The heuristics tested here used Œ± = 1 and Œ≥ = 0.1, where
Œ± and Œ≥ are described in [14, Section 6.5]. The estimated value function Q was initialized to return zero for
every state-action pair.
4.2. Testing Framework
Many other decisions were made regarding a range of issues in setting up the Ô¨Ånal testing framework. These are
summarized below.

2262

Lisa Peairs et al. / Procedia Computer Science 4 (2011) 2257‚Äì2266

4.2.1. Matrices
The 30 test matrices all ccme from the University of Florida Sparse Matrix Collection [15]. While most of the
matrices came from computational Ô¨Çuid dynamics applications, others came from applications including acoustics
and circuit simulation. More importantly, the set of matrices selected had signiÔ¨Åcant overlap with the matrices used
in [5] and [6] in order to enable more meaningful comparisons with those results. Of the 12 matrices in [5], 5 are also
in this test set; of the 20 matrices in [6], 10 are also in this test set.
The solution vector was always the vector of all 1s and the right hand side b = Ax was calculated accordingly.
4.2.2. Preconditioner
In practice a preconditioner is almost always used in conjunction with any iterative solver [16]. Two incomplete
LU preconditioners were tested in these experiments.
One was RILUK, a level-based incomplete LU preconditioner described in [17]. RILUK takes two parameters:
level, which controls the amount of Ô¨Åll and therefore the overall space required for the preconditioner, and œâ, which
speciÔ¨Åes how diagonal values dropped during the incomplete factorization are handled. Experiments were conducted
with six level values from 0 through 5, and with eight œâ values between 0.00 and 0.95. These ranges include
commonly recommended values.
The other was ILUT, a popular value-based incomplete LU preconditioner proposed in [18]. ILUT takes two
parameters: lfil, which controls overall space required by the incomplete factorization, and thresh, which determines how large an entry must be to be considered signiÔ¨Åcant. Experiments were conducted with 18 lfil values
between 1 and 50 inclusive and four thresh values between 0.0001 and 0.1. Again, these ranges include values that
are commonly used in practice.
4.2.3. GMRES(m) settings
The solver was judged to have converged when the norm of the residual was no greater than 10‚àí8 ; this is a
commonly used value in practice. Most experiments were run with the maximum number of iterations set to 600,
although some data was collected with higher values in order to see whether that made a diÔ¨Äerence.
4.2.4. Data Collection
Because there is a random component to the randGMRES, GMRES RL, and angleGMRES RL heuristics, each
computation was executed 10 times. Unless otherwise speciÔ¨Åed, the number of iterations reported as being required
by a computation refers to the average number of iterations required over those 10 runs.
4.2.5. Implementation
The heuristics described in Section 4.1 were implemented in C++ and the code was integrated with that in BPKIT [17].
5. Results
Data was collected for over 750, 000 combinations of the matrix, the preconditioner, the heuristic for choosing the
restart value, the parameter values for the preconditioner, and the set of allowable restart values. In addition to being
analyzed for the eÔ¨Äectiveness of the diÔ¨Äerent heuristics for choosing the restarts, the data was also analyzed for the
eÔ¨Äect of diÔ¨Äerent preconditioners and parameter values.
The main results presented here are:
1. the eÔ¨Äect of varying m and
2. the eÔ¨Äectiveness of the diÔ¨Äerent heuristics for choosing m.
Additional observations are noted in Section 5.3.

